@Ember421 @Tpsmyth01 @DMoKreis @MeredithAngwin Problem with random inputs is that some of the industries are capital intensive. That’s why I said 140% of *peak* (ie 3x average), which leaves industry running full blast almost all the time.

column4: @VorherrMark @mattjcan I think you should look at our experiment in South Australia. Coal demolished. Wind and solar installed. However, because it is so variable, 40% of power on average, is provided by gas and imported coal-fired generation. Same result in the UK, and Germany.

column4:
I've seen many tweets by renewable energy enthusiasts claiming that keeping the grid stable at high shares of wind and solar is not an issue. They infer that from a good track record so far, e.g. in Germany. 
The track record is good indeed, but don't ever think it's simple.

@Schingkenspigg1 @ecomodernist1 @lukavalas Renewables are most expensive by far.

Why?

Because sun doesn't shine and wind doesn't  blow 24/7.

So you have to build double capacity - like Germany (gas and coal).

Solar panel doesn't have inertia - can't power modern grid...

@ChristoThurston Germany has more than 100, 000mw of solar and wind. This is helpful but it is not a solution.  Thier grid is under pressure because their gas power stations don't have gas and the draught in Europe doesn't allow the nuclear fleet to work properly (baseload)

We need gas turbines!
